# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aircraft-fuel-system
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/accessory-drive] The **accessory drive** is a gearbox that forms part of a gas turbine engine.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/accessory-drive] Although not part of the engine's core, it drives the accessories – such as generators, pumps for fuel and lubrication oil, air compressors, hydraulic pumps and engine starters – that are otherwise essential for the operation of the engine or the aircraft on which it is mounted.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/accessory-drive] Accessory drives on large engines handle between 400–500 hp.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/accessory-drive] Power for the accessory drive is taken from the central shaft linking the turbine and compressor sections of the engine.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/accessory-drive] This requires an internal gearbox that couples the drive to a radial driveshaft or *towershaft* that drives an external gearbox.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/accessory-drive] The design of the internal gearbox is complicated by the heat and small space available in which to connect the driveshaft.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/accessory-drive] It is usually placed between the compressor outlet and the combustor.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/accessory-drive] In turboprops or designs with centrifugal compressors, it may be placed ahead of the compressor.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/accessory-drive] For two-shaft designs, an accessory drive will be taken from the high-pressure shaft, i.e. the outer and shorter of the two concentric shafts.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/accessory-drive] This shaft comes up to speed more quickly when the engine is started.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/accessory-drive] The drive and accessory gearboxes may also be split in two, one driven from each engine shaft, so as to distribute their loads.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/accessory-drive] The engine-critical systems, including the starter drive, are arranged on the high-pressure shaft, with aircraft systems on the low-pressure shaft.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/accessory-drive] The high-pressure shaft also rotates faster than the low-pressure shaft, which may influence the distribution of accessories.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/accessory-drive] To make the best use of the limited space for the driveshaft and internal gearbox, the driveshaft runs at high speed, thus allowing it to be of small diameter.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/accessory-drive] This reduces the disruption to the airflow and the size of the hollow fairing that encloses it.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/accessory-drive] If it is not possible to arrange a single straight path for the driveshaft, it may be arranged in two sections and linked by an intermediate gearbox.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/accessory-drive] This is most commonly required for high-bypass turbofans with large diameter fans.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/accessory-drive] The packaging of an engine within its nacelle is a complicated task.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/accessory-drive] The accessory drive is usually arranged as a curved casing, so that the various accessories are mounted close to the engine.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/accessory-drive] The casing is a pair of light alloy castings.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/accessory-drive] Separate machined mounting pads are provided for each accessory.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/accessory-drive] The drive within the casing is provided by a train of spur gears.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/accessory-drive] Accessories are arranged on both sides of the driveshaft entry, in reducing order of their speed.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/accessory-drive] The gears are usually plain spur gears, running in roller bearings.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/accessory-drive] Idler gears are commonly used between them, to increase the spacing between accessories.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/accessory-drive] Helical gears are sometimes used for the high-torque drives, typically the starter, as these give smoother running.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/accessory-drive] However helical gears also generate an end-thrust, which then requires a more complicated thrust bearing to support them.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/accessory-drive] The complexity of an accessory drive and its gears is so great that they were used as a theme by the anthropomorphic illustrator Boris Artzybasheff in advertising for the Avco Lycoming company, who were making drive gearboxes for the Westinghouse J40 engine.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/accessory-drive] In some engines, bleed air is also tapped to provide power for accessories, as well as a mechanical shaft drive.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/accessory-drive] Bleed air is particularly useful when a source of compressed air is specifically needed, either to pressurise cabin air, or as a supply of cooling air to other components (to avoid excess heat, this is taken for a low-pressure tapping, or from the LP compressor of a two-shaft engine).
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/accessory-drive] One important use for bleed air is for cross-starting of other engines in a multi-engine aircraft.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/accessory-drive] Additional facilities are provided for a centrifugal oil breather, to separate the drive lubricating oil from the overboard breather air vent.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/accessory-drive] Also access for hand-turning the engine, during ground maintenance.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The procedure allows the receiving aircraft to remain airborne longer, extending its range or loiter time.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] A series of air refuelling can give range limited only by crew's physiological needs (like fatigue) and engineering factors such as engine oil consumption.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Because the receiver aircraft is topped-off with extra fuel in the air, air refuelling can allow a takeoff with a greater payload which could be weapons, cargo, or personnel: the maximum takeoff weight is maintained by carrying less fuel and topping up once airborne.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Aerial refuelling has also been considered as a means to reduce fuel consumption on long-distance flights greater than 3,000 nautical miles (5,600 km; 3,500 mi).
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Potential fuel savings in the range of 35–40 % have been estimated for long-haul flights (including the fuel used during the tanker missions).
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Usually, the aircraft providing the fuel is specially designed for the task, although refuelling pods may be fitted to existing aircraft designs in the case of "probe-and-drogue" systems.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Some of the earliest experiments in aerial refueling took place in the 1920s; two slow-flying aircraft flew in formation, with a hose run down from a hand-held fuel tank on one aircraft and placed into the usual fuel filler of the other.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The first mid-air refueling, based on the development of Alexander P. de Seversky, between two planes occurred on 25 June 1923, between two Airco DH-4B biplanes of the United States Army Air Service.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] An endurance record was set by three DH-4Bs (a receiver and two tankers) on 27–28 August 1923, in which the receiver airplane remained aloft for more than 37 hours using nine mid-air refuels to transfer 687 US gallons (2,600 L) of aviation gasoline and 38 US gallons (140 L) of engine oil.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The same crews demonstrated the utility of the technique on 25 October 1923, when a DH-4 flew from Sumas, Washington, on the Canada–United States border, to Tijuana, Mexico, landing in San Diego, using mid-air refuelings at Eugene, Oregon, and Sacramento, California.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Similar trial demonstrations of mid-air refueling technique took place at the Royal Aircraft Establishment in England and by the Armée de l'Air in France in the same year, but these early experiments were not yet regarded as a practical proposition, and were generally dismissed as stunts.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] As the 1920s progressed, greater numbers of aviation enthusiasts vied to set new aerial long-distance records, using inflight air refueling.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] One such enthusiast, who would revolutionize aerial refueling was Sir Alan Cobham, member of the Royal Flying Corps in World War I, and a pioneer of long-distance aviation.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] During the 1920s, he made long-distance flights to places as far afield as Africa and Australia and he began experimenting with the possibilities of in-flight refueling to extend the range of flight.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Cobham was one of the founding directors of Airspeed Limited, an aircraft manufacturing company that went on to produce a specially adapted Airspeed Courier that Cobham used for his early experiments with in-flight refueling.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] This craft was eventually modified by Airspeed to Cobham's specification, for a non-stop flight from London to India, using in-flight refueling to extend the plane's flight duration.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Meanwhile, in 1929, a group of US Army Air Corps fliers, led by then Major Carl Spaatz, set an endurance record of over 150 hours with a Fokker C-2A named the *Question Mark* over Los Angeles.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Between 11 June and 4 July 1930, the brothers John, Kenneth, Albert, and Walter Hunter set a new record of 553 hours 40 minutes over Chicago using two Stinson SM-1 Detroiters as refueler and receiver.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Aerial refueling remained a very dangerous process until 1935, when brothers Fred and Al Key demonstrated a spill-free refueling nozzle, designed by A.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] They exceeded the Hunters' record by nearly 100 hours in a Curtiss Robin monoplane, staying aloft for more than 27 days.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The US was mainly concerned about transatlantic flights for faster postal service between Europe and America.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Irving Glover, the second assistant postmaster, wrote an extensive article for *Popular Mechanics* concerning the challenges and the need for such a regular service.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] In his article he even mentioned the use of aerial refueling after takeoff as a possible solution.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] At Le Bourget Airport near Paris, the Aéro-Club de France and the 34th Aviation Regiment of the French Air Force were able to demonstrate passing fuel between machines at the annual aviation fete at Vincennes in 1928.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The UK's Royal Aircraft Establishment was also running mid-air refueling trials, with the aim to use this technique to extend the range of the long-distance flying boats that serviced the British Empire.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] By 1931 they had demonstrated refueling between two Vickers Virginias, with fuel flow controlled by an automatic valve on the hose which would cut off if contact was lost.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Royal Air Force officer Richard Atcherley had observed the dangerous aerial-refueling techniques in use at barnstorming events in the US and determined to create a workable system.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] While posted to the Middle East he developed and patented his 'crossover' system in 1934, in which the tanker trailed a large hooked line that would reel in a similar dropped line from the receiver, allowing the refueling to commence.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] In 1935, Cobham sold off the airline Cobham Air Routes Ltd to Olley Air Service and turned to the development of inflight refueling, founding the company Flight Refuelling Ltd.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Atcherly's system was bought up by Cobham's company, and with some refinement and continuous improvement through the late '30s, it became the first practical refueling system.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Sir Alan Cobham's *grappled-line looped-hose* air-to-air refueling system borrowed from techniques patented by David Nicolson and John Lord, and was publicly demonstrated for the first time in 1935.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] In the system the receiver aircraft, at one time an Airspeed Courier, trailed a steel cable which was then grappled by a line shot from the tanker, a Handley Page Type W10.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The line was then drawn back into the tanker where the receiver's cable was connected to the refueling hose.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The receiver could then haul back in its cable bringing the hose to it.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Once the hose was connected, the tanker climbed sufficiently above the receiver aircraft to allow the fuel to flow under gravity.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] When Cobham was developing his system, he saw the need as purely for long-range transoceanic commercial aircraft flights, but modern aerial refueling is used exclusively by military aircraft.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] In 1934, Cobham had founded Flight Refuelling Ltd (FRL) and by 1938 had used its *looped-hose* system to refuel aircraft as large as the Short Empire flying boat *Cambria* from an Armstrong Whitworth AW.23.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Handley Page Harrows were used in the 1939 trials to perform aerial refueling of the Empire flying boats for regular transatlantic crossings.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] From 5 August to 1 October 1939, sixteen crossings of the Atlantic were made by Empire flying boats, with fifteen crossings using FRL's aerial refueling system.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] After the sixteen crossings further trials were suspended due to the outbreak of World War II.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] After the war ended, the USAF bought a small number of FRL looped-hose units and fitted a number of B-29s as tankers to refuel specially equipped B-29s and later B-50s.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The USAF made only one major change in the system used by the RAF.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] This air-to-air refueling system was used by the B-50 Superfortress *Lucky Lady II* of the 43rd Bomb Wing to make its famous first non-stop around-the-world flight in 1949.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] From 26 February to 3 March 1949, *Lucky Lady II* flew non-stop around the world in 94 hours and 1 minute, a feat made possible by four aerial refuelings from four pairs of KB-29M tankers of the 43d ARS.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Before the mission, crews of the 43rd had experienced only a single operational air refueling contact.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The flight started and ended at Carswell Air Force Base in Fort Worth, Texas with the refuelings accomplished over the Azores, Saudi Arabia, the Pacific Ocean near Guam, and between Hawaii and the West Coast.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] In post-war trials the RAF used a modified Lancaster tanker employing the much improved probe-and-drogue system, with a modified Gloster Meteor F.3 jet fighter, serial *EE397*, fitted with a nose-mounted probe.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] On 7 August 1949, the Meteor flown by FRL test pilot Pat Hornidge took off from Tarrant Rushton and remained airborne for 12 hours and 3 minutes, receiving 2,352 imperial gallons (10,690 L) of fuel in ten refuelings from a Lancaster tanker.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Hornidge flew an overall distance of 3,600 mi (5,800 km), achieving a new jet endurance record.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Modern specialized tanker aircraft have equipment specially designed for the task of offloading fuel to the receiver aircraft, based on drogue and probe, even at the higher speeds modern jet aircraft typically need to remain airborne.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] In January 1948, General Carl Spaatz, then the first Chief of Staff of the new United States Air Force, made aerial refueling a top priority of the service.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] In March 1948, the USAF purchased two sets of FRL's looped-hose in-flight refueling equipment, which had been in practical use with British Overseas Airways Corporation (BOAC) since 1946, and manufacturing rights to the system.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] FRL also provided a year of technical assistance.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The sets were immediately installed in two Boeing B-29 Superfortresses, with plans to equip 80 B-29s.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Flight testing began in May 1948 at Wright-Patterson Air Force Base, Ohio, and was so successful that in June orders went out to equip all new B-50s and subsequent bombers with receiving equipment.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Two dedicated air refueling units were formed on 30 June 1948: the 43d Air Refueling Squadron at Davis-Monthan Air Force Base, Arizona, and the 509th Air Refueling Squadron at Walker Air Force Base, New Mexico.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The first ARS aircraft used FRL's looped-hose refueling system, but testing with a boom system followed quickly in the autumn of 1948.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The flying boom is a rigid, telescoping tube with movable flight control surfaces that a boom operator on the tanker aircraft extends and inserts into a receptacle on the receiving aircraft.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] KC-135 Stratotanker, KC-10 Extender, KC-46 Pegasus) have a single boom and can refuel one aircraft at a time with this mechanism.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] In the late 1940s, General Curtis LeMay, commander of the Strategic Air Command (SAC), asked Boeing to develop a refueling system that could transfer fuel at a higher rate than had been possible with earlier systems using flexible hoses, resulting in the flying boom system.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The B-29 was the first to employ the boom, and between 1950 and 1951, 116 original B-29s, designated KB-29Ps, were converted at the Boeing plant at Renton, Washington.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Boeing went on to develop the world's first production aerial tanker, the KC-97 Stratofreighter, a piston-engined Boeing Stratocruiser (USAF designation C-97 Stratofreighter) with a Boeing-developed flying boom and extra kerosene (jet fuel) tanks feeding the boom.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The Stratocruiser airliner itself was developed from the B-29 bomber after World War II.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] In the KC-97, the mixed gasoline/kerosene fuel system was clearly not desirable and it was obvious that a jet-powered tanker aircraft would be the next development, having a single type of fuel for both its own engines and for passing to receiver aircraft.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] It was no surprise that, after the KC-97, Boeing began receiving contracts from the USAF to build jet tankers based on the Boeing 367-80 (Dash-80) airframe.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The result was the Boeing KC-135 Stratotanker, of which 732 were built.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The flying boom is attached to the rear of the tanker aircraft.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The attachment is gimballed, allowing the boom to move with the receiver aircraft.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The boom contains a rigid pipe to transfer fuel.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The fuel pipe ends in a nozzle with a flexible ball joint.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The nozzle mates to the "receptacle" in the receiver aircraft during fuel transfer.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] A poppet valve in the end of the nozzle prevents fuel from exiting the tube until the nozzle properly mates with the receiver's refueling receptacle.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Once properly mated, toggles in the receptacle engage the nozzle, holding it locked during fuel transfer.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The "flying" boom is so named because flight control surfaces, small movable airfoils that are often in a V-tail configuration, are used to move the boom by creating aerodynamic forces.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] They are actuated hydraulically and controlled by the boom operator using a control stick.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The boom operator also telescopes the boom to make the connection with the receiver's receptacle.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] To complete an aerial refueling, the tanker and receiver aircraft rendezvous, flying in formation.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The receiver moves to a position behind the tanker, within safe limits of travel for the boom, aided by director lights or directions radioed by the boom operator.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Once in position, the operator extends the boom to make contact with the receiver aircraft.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Once in contact, fuel is pumped through the boom into the receiver aircraft.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] While in contact, the receiver pilot must continue to fly within the "air refueling envelope", the area in which contact with the boom is safe.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Moving outside of this envelope can damage the boom or lead to mid-air collision, for example the 1966 Palomares B-52 crash.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] If the receiving aircraft approaches the outer limits of the envelope, the boom operator will command the receiver pilot to correct their position and disconnect the boom if necessary.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] When the desired amount of fuel has been transferred, the two aircraft disconnect and the receiver aircraft departs the formation.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] When not in use, the boom is stored flush with the bottom of the tanker's fuselage to minimize drag.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] In the KC-97 and KC-135 the boom operator lies prone, while the operator is seated in the KC-10, all viewing operations through a window at the tail.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The KC-46 seats two operators at the front of the aircraft viewing camera video on 3D screens.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The US Air Force fixed-wing aircraft use the flying boom system, along with Australia (KC-30A), the Netherlands (KDC-10), Israel (modified Boeing 707), Japan (KC-767), Turkey (KC-135Rs), and Iran (Boeing 707 and 747).
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The system allows higher fuel flow rates (up to 1,000 US gallons (3,800 L) / 6,500 pounds (2,900 kg) per minute for the KC-135, but does require a boom operator, and can only refuel one aircraft at a time.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The probe-and-drogue refueling method employs a flexible hose that trails from the tanker aircraft.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The *drogue* (or *para-drogue*), sometimes called a *basket*, is a fitting resembling a shuttlecock, attached at its narrow end (like the "cork" nose of a shuttlecock) with a valve to a flexible hose.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The drogue stabilizes the hose in flight and provides a funnel to aid insertion of the receiver aircraft probe into the hose.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The hose connects to a hose drum unit (HDU).
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] When not in use, the hose/drogue is reeled completely into the HDU.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The receiver has a *probe*, which is a rigid, protruding or pivoted retractable arm placed on the aircraft's nose or fuselage to make the connection.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Most modern versions of the probe are usually designed to be retractable, and are retracted when not in use, particularly on high-speed aircraft.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] At the end of the probe is a valve that is closed until it mates with the drogue's forward internal receptacle, after which it opens and allows fuel to pass from tanker to receiver.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The valves in the probe and drogue that are most commonly used are to a NATO standard and were originally developed by the company Flight Refuelling Limited in the UK and deployed in the late 1940s and 1950s.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] This standardization enables drogue-equipped tanker aircraft from many nations to refuel probe-equipped aircraft from other nations.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The NATO-standard probe system incorporates shear rivets that attach the refueling valve to the end of the probe.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] This is so that if a large side or vertical load develops while in contact with the drogue, the rivets shear and the fuel valve breaks off, rather than the probe or receiver aircraft suffering structural damage.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] A so-called "broken probe" (actually a broken fuel valve, as described above) may happen if poor flying technique is used by the receiver pilot, or in turbulence.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Sometimes the valve is retained in the tanker drogue and prevents further refueling from that drogue until removed during ground maintenance.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] A "buddy store" or "buddy pod" is an external pod loaded on an aircraft hardpoint that contains a hose and drogue system (HDU).
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Buddy stores allow fighter / bomber aircraft to be reconfigured for "buddy tanking" other aircraft.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] This allows an air combat force without dedicated/specialized tanker support (for instance, a carrier air wing) to extend the range of its strike aircraft.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] In other cases, using the buddy store method allows a carrier-based aircraft to take-off with a heavier than usual weapon load, but less fuel than might be necessary for its tasking.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The aircraft would then be topped-up with fuel from an HDU-equipped "buddy" tanker, a method previously used by the Royal Navy in operating its Supermarine Scimitar, de Havilland Sea Vixen, and Blackburn Buccaneers; in the Buccaneer's case using a bomb-bay-mounted tank and HDU.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The tanker aircraft flies straight and level and extends the hose/drogue, which is allowed to trail out behind and below the tanker under normal aerodynamic forces.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The pilot of the receiver aircraft extends the probe (if required) and uses normal flight controls to "fly" the refueling probe directly into the basket.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] This requires a closure rate of about two knots (walking speed) to push the hose several feet into the HDU and solidly couple the probe and drogue.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Too little closure will cause an incomplete connection and no fuel flow (or occasionally leaking fuel).
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Too much closure is dangerous because it can trigger a strong transverse oscillation in the hose, severing the probe tip.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The optimal approach is from behind and below (not level with) the drogue.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Because the drogue is relatively light (typically soft canvas webbing) and subject to aerodynamic forces, it can be pushed around by the bow wave of approaching aircraft, exacerbating engagement even in smooth air.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] After initial contact, the hose and drogue is pushed forward by the receiver a certain distance (typically, a few feet), and the hose is reeled slowly back onto its drum in the HDU.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] This opens the tanker's main refueling valve allowing fuel to flow to the drogue under the appropriate pressure (assuming the tanker crew has energized the pump).
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Tension on the hose is aerodynamically 'balanced' by a motor in the HDU so that as the receiver aircraft moves fore and aft, the hose retracts and extends, thus preventing bends in the hose that would cause undue side loads on the probe.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Fuel flow is typically indicated by illumination of a green light near the HDU.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] If the hose is pushed in too far or not far enough, a cutoff switch will inhibit fuel flow, which is typically accompanied by an amber light.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Disengagement is commanded by the tanker pilot with a red light.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The US Navy, Marine Corps, and some US Army aircraft refuel using the "hose-and-drogue" system, as do most aircraft flown by western European militaries.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The Soviet Union also used a hose-and-drogue system, dubbed UPAZ, and thus later Russian aircraft may be equipped with probe and drogue.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The Chinese PLAF has a fleet of Xian H-6 bombers modified for aerial refueling, and plans to add Russian Ilyushin Il-78 aerial refueling tankers.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Tankers can be equipped with multipoint hose-and-drogue systems, allowing them to refuel two (or more) aircraft simultaneously, reducing time spent refueling by as much as 75% for a four-aircraft strike package.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] USAF KC-135 and French Air Force KC-135FR refueling-boom equipped tankers can be field-converted to a probe-and-drogue system using a special adapter unit.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] In this configuration, the tanker retains its articulated boom, but has a hose/drogue at the end of it instead of the usual nozzle.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The tanker boom operator holds the boom still while the receiver aircraft flies the probe into the basket.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Unlike the soft canvas basket used in most drogue systems, the adapter units use a steel basket, grimly known as the "iron maiden" by naval aviators because of its unforgiving nature.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Soft drogues can be contacted slightly off center, wherein the probe is guided into the hose receptacle by the canvas drogue.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The metal drogue, when contacted even slightly off center, will pivot out of place, potentially "slapping" the aircraft's fuselage and causing damage.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The other major difference with this system is that when contacted, the hose does not "retract" into an HDU.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Instead, the hose bends depending on how far it is pushed toward the boom.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] If it is pushed too far, it can loop around the probe or nose of the aircraft, damage the windscreen, or cause contact with the rigid boom.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] If not pushed far enough, the probe will disengage, halting fueling.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Because of a much smaller position-keeping tolerance, staying properly connected to a KC-135 adapter unit is considerably more difficult than staying in a traditional hose/drogue configuration.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] When fueling is complete, the receiver carefully backs off until the probe refueling valve disconnects from the valve in the basket.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Off center disengagements, like engagements, can cause the drogue to "prang" the probe and/or strike the aircraft's fuselage.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Some tankers have both a boom and one or more complete hose-and-drogue systems.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The USAF KC-10 has both a flying boom and a separate hose-and-drogue system manufactured by Cobham.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Both are on the aircraft centerline at the tail of the aircraft, so only one can be used at once.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] However, such a system allows all types of probe- and receptacle-equipped aircraft to be refueled in a single mission, without landing to install an adapter.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] A small number of Soviet Tu-4s and Tu-16s (the tanker variant was Tu-16Z), used a wing-to-wing method.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Similar to the probe-and-drogue method but more complicated, the tanker aircraft released a flexible hose from its wingtip.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] An aircraft flying alongside had to catch the hose with a special lock under its wingtip.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] After the hose was locked and the connection was established, the fuel was pumped.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] This was the method used on the Question Mark endurance flight in 1929.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The probe-and-drogue system is not compatible with flying boom equipment, creating a problem for military planners where mixed forces are involved.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Incompatibility can also complicate the procurement of new systems.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The Royal Canadian Air Force currently wish to purchase the F-35A, which can only refuel via the flying boom, but only possess probe-and-drogue refuelers.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The potential cost of converting F-35As to probe-and-drogue refueling (as is used on US Navy & Marine Corps F-35Bs and F-35Cs) added to the early-2010s political controversy which surrounded F-35 procurement within the RCAF.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] This also ensured that a first strike against the bombers' airfields could not obliterate the US's ability to retaliate by bomber.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] In 1958, Valiant tankers in the UK were developed with one HDU mounted in the bomb-bay.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Valiant tankers of 214 Squadron were used to demonstrate radius of action by refueling a Valiant bomber non-stop from UK to Singapore in 1960 and a Vulcan bomber to Australia in 1961.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Other UK exercises involving refueling aircraft from Valiant tankers included Javelin and Lightning fighters, also Vulcan and Victor bombers.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] For instance, in 1962 a squadron of Javelin air defense aircraft was refueled in stages from the UK to India and back (exercise "Shiksha").
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] After the retirement of the Valiant in 1965, the Handley Page Victor took over the UK refueling role and had three hoses (HDUs).
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] These were a fuselage-mounted HDU and a refueling pod on each wing.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The center hose could refuel any probe-equipped aircraft, the wing pods could refuel the more maneuverable fighter/ground attack types.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] A byproduct of this development effort and the building of large numbers of tankers was that these tankers were also available to refuel cargo aircraft, fighter aircraft, and ground attack aircraft, in addition to bombers, for ferrying to distant theaters of operations.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] This was much used during the Vietnam War, when many aircraft could not have covered the transoceanic distances without aerial refueling, even with intermediate bases such as Hickam Air Force Base, Hawaii and Kadena Air Base, Okinawa.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] In addition to allowing the transport of the aircraft themselves, the cargo aircraft could also carry matériel, supplies, and personnel to Vietnam without landing to refuel.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] KC-135s were also frequently used for refueling of air combat missions from air bases in Thailand.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The USAF SR-71 Blackbird strategic reconnaissance aircraft made frequent use of air-to-air refueling.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Indeed, design considerations of the aircraft made its mission impossible without aerial refueling.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Based at Beale AFB in central California, SR-71s had to be forward-deployed to Europe and Japan prior to flying actual reconnaissance missions.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] These trans-Pacific and trans-Atlantic flights during deployment were impossible without aerial refueling.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The SR-71's designers traded takeoff performance for better high-speed, high-altitude performance, necessitating takeoff with less-than-full fuel tanks from even the longest runways.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Once airborne, the Blackbird would accelerate to supersonic speed using afterburners to facilitate structural heating and expansion.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The magnitude of temperature changes experienced by the SR-71, from parked to its maximum speed, resulted in significant expansion of its structural parts in cruise flight.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] To allow for the expansion, the Blackbird's parts had to fit loosely when cold, so loosely, in fact, that the Blackbird constantly leaked fuel before heating expanded the airframe enough to seal its fuel tanks.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Following the supersonic dash the SR-71 would then rendezvous with a tanker to fill its now nearly empty tanks before proceeding on its mission.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] This was referred to as the *LTTR* (for "Launch To Tanker Rendezvous") profile.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] LTTR had the added advantage of providing an operational test of the Blackbird's refueling capability within minutes after takeoff, enabling a Return-To-Launch-Site abort capability if necessary.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] At its most efficient altitude and speed, the Blackbird was capable of flying for many hours without refueling.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The SR-71 used a special fuel, JP-7, with a very high flash point to withstand the extreme skin temperatures generated during Mach 3+ cruise flight.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] While JP-7 could be used by other aircraft, its burn characteristics posed problems in certain situations (such as high-altitude, emergency engine starts) that made it less than optimal for aircraft other than the SR-71.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Normally, all the fuel aboard a tanker aircraft may be either offloaded, or burned by the tanker as necessary.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] To make this possible, the KC-135 fuel system incorporated gravity draining and pumps to allow moving fuel from tank to tank depending on mission needs.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] SR-71 aircraft were refueled exclusively by KC-135Q tankers.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Tankers are considered "force multipliers", because they convey considerable tactical advantages.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Primarily, aerial refueling adds to the combat radius of attack, fighter and bombers aircraft, and allows patrol aircraft to remain airborne longer, thereby reducing the number of aircraft necessary to accomplish a given mission.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Aerial refueling can also mitigate basing issues that might otherwise place limitations on combat payload.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Combat aircraft operating from airfields with shorter runways must limit their takeoff weight, which could mean a choice between range (fuel) and combat payload (munitions).
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Aerial refueling, however, eliminates many of these basing difficulties because a combat aircraft can take off with a full combat payload and refuel immediately.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Even as the first practical methods for aerial refueling were being developed, military planners had already envisioned what missions could be greatly enhanced by using such techniques.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] In the emerging Cold War climate of the late 1940s, the ability for bombers to perform increasingly long distance missions would enable targets to be struck even from air bases on a different continent.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Thus, it became commonplace for nuclear-armed strategic bombers to be equipped with aerial refueling apparatus and for it to be used to facilitate long distance patrols.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] During the late 1950s, aerial refueling had become so prevalent amongst the bombers operated by the US Air Force's Strategic Air Command that many, such as the Convair B-58 Hustler, would operate largely or entirely out of bases in the continental United States while maintaining strategic reach.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] This practice was promoted to address security concerns as well as diplomatic objections from some overseas states that did not want nuclear weapons kept on their soil.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] While development of the Avro Vulcan strategic bomber was underway, British officials recognised that its operational flexibility could be improved by the provision of in-flight refueling equipment.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Accordingly, from the 16th aircraft to be completed onwards, the Vulcan was furnished with in-flight refueling receiving equipment.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] While continuous airborne patrols were flown by the RAF for a time, these were deemed to be untenable, and the refueling mechanisms across the Vulcan fleet largely fell into disuse during the 1960s.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] When the RAF chose to optimise its bomber fleet away from high-altitude flight and towards low-level penetration missions, bombers such as the Handley Page Victor were fitted with aerial refueling probes and additional fuel tanks to counter the decreased range from the shift in flight profile.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] During the mid-1950s, to deliver France's independent nuclear deterrent, work commenced on what would become the Dassault Mirage IV supersonic bomber.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The dimensions of this bomber was greatly determined by the viability of aerial refueling, with work on an enlarged variant of the Mirage IV ultimately being aborted in favour of a greater reliance upon aerial tanker aircraft instead.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] In order to refuel the Mirage IVA fleet, France purchased 14 (12 plus 2 spares) US Boeing C-135F tankers.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Mirage IVAs also often operated in pairs, with one aircraft carrying a weapon and the other carrying fuel tanks and a buddy refueling pack, allowing it to refuel its partner en route to the target.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] While able to strike at numerous targets inside of the Soviet Union, the inability for the Mirage IV to return from some missions had been a point of controversy during the aircraft's design phase.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] On 6 July 1951, the first combat air refueling of fighter-type aircraft took place over Korea.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Three RF-80As launched from Taegu with the modified tip-tanks and rendezvoused with a tanker offshore of Wonsan, North Korea.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Through in-flight refueling, the RF-80s effectively doubled their range, which enabled them to photograph valuable targets in North Korea.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] During the Vietnam War, it was common for USAF fighter-bombers flying from Thailand to North Vietnam to refuel from KC-135s en route to their target.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Besides extending their range, this enabled the F-105s and F-4 Phantoms to carry more bombs and rockets.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Tankers were also available for refueling on the way back if necessary.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] In addition to ferrying aircraft across the Pacific Ocean, aerial refueling made it possible for battle-damaged fighters, with heavily leaking fuel tanks, to hook up to the tankers and let the tanker feed its engine(s) until the point where they could glide to the base and land.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The US Navy frequently used carrier-based aerial tankers like the KA-3 Skywarrior to refuel Navy and Marine aircraft such as the F-4, A-4 Skyhawk, A-6 Intruder, and A-7 Corsair II.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] This was particularly useful when a pilot returning from an airstrike was having difficulty landing and was running low on jet fuel.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] This gave them fuel for more attempts at landing for a successful "trap" on an aircraft carrier.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The KA-3 could also refuel fighters on extended Combat Air Patrol.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] USMC jets based in South Vietnam and Thailand also used USMC KC-130 Hercules transports for air-to-air refueling on missions.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] During late August 1970, a pair of HH-53C helicopters performed the first Trans-Pacific flight by a helicopter, flying from Eglin AFB in Florida to Danang in South Vietnam.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] In addition to making multiple en route stops to refuel on the ground, aerial refueling was also used in this display of the type's long-range capabilities.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The flight proved to be roughly four times faster than the traditional dispatching of rotorcraft to the theatre by ship.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] During the 1980s Iran–Iraq War, the Iranian Air Force maintained at least one KC 707-3J9C aerial tanker, which the Islamic Republic had inherited from the Shah's government.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] This was used most effectively on 4 April 1981, refueling eight IRIAF F-4 Phantoms on long-range sorties into Iraq to bomb the H-3 Al Walid airfield near the Jordanian border, destroying 27–50 Iraqi fighter jets and bombers.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] However, the Iranian Air Force was forced to cancel its 180-day air offensive and attempts to control Iranian airspace due to unsustainable rates of attrition.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The Israeli Air Force has a fleet of Boeing 707s equipped with a boom refueling system similar to the KC-135; this system has the Israeli name *Ram*, used to refuel and extend the range of fighter bombers such as the F-15I and F-16I for deterrent and strike missions.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] They are nearing 60 years old and Israel does not disclose the number of tankers in their fleet.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] As of 2021 Israel has ordered four of a planned eight Boeing KC-46 Pegasus boom refueling tankers and has requested that the first two aircraft be fast-tracked for delivery in 2022 when they were to be delivered in 2023.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The JPost editor wrote "The US State Department approved the possible sale of up to eight KC-46 tanker aircraft and related equipment to Israel for an estimated cost of $2.4 billion last March (i.e.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] During the Falklands War, aerial refueling played a vital role in all of the successful Argentine attacks against the Royal Navy.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The Argentine Air Force had only two KC-130H Hercules available and they were used to refuel both Air Force and Navy A-4 Skyhawks and Navy Super Etendards in their Exocet strikes.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The Hercules on several occasions approached the islands (where the Sea Harriers were in patrol) to search and guide the A-4s in their returning flights.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] On one of those flights (callsign *Jaguar*) one of the KC-130s went to rescue a damaged A-4 and delivered 39,000 lb (18,000 kg) of fuel while carrying it to its airfield at San Julian.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] However, the Mirage IIIs and Daggers lack of air refueling capability prevented them from achieving better results.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The Mirages were unable to reach the islands with a strike payload, and the Daggers could do so only for a five-minute strike flight.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] On the British side, air refueling was carried out by the Handley Page Victor K.2 and, after the Argentine surrender, by modified C-130 Hercules tankers.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] These aircraft aided deployments from the UK to the Ascension Island staging post in the Atlantic and further deployments south of bomber, transport and maritime patrol aircraft.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The most famous refueling missions were the 8,000 nmi (15,000 km) "Operation Black Buck" sorties which used 14 Victor tankers to allow an Avro Vulcan bomber (with a flying reserve bomber) to attack the Argentine-captured airfield at Port Stanley on the Falkland Islands.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] With all the aircraft flying from Ascension, the tankers themselves needed refueling.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The raids were the longest-range bombing raids in history until surpassed by the Boeing B-52s flying from the continental USA to bomb Iraq in the 1991 Gulf War and later B-2 flights.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] During the time of Operation Desert Shield, the military buildup to the Persian Gulf War, US Air Force Boeing KC-135s & McDonnell Douglas KC-10As, and USMC KC-130 Hercules aircraft were deployed to forward air bases in England, Diego Garcia, and Saudi Arabia.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Aircraft stationed in Saudi Arabia normally maintained an orbit in the Saudi–Iraqi neutral zone, informally known as "Frisbee", and refueled coalition aircraft whenever necessary.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Two side by side tracks over central Saudi Arabia called "Prune" and "Raisin" featured 2–4 basket equipped KC-135 tankers each and were used by Navy aircraft from the Red Sea Battle Force.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Large Navy strike groups from the Red Sea would send A-6 tankers to the Prune and Raisin tracks ahead of the strike aircraft arriving to top off and take up station to the right of the Air Force tankers thereby providing an additional tanking point.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] RAF Handley Page Victor and Vickers VC10 tankers were also used to refuel British and coalition aircraft and were popular with the US Navy for their docile basket behavior and having three point refueling stations.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] An additional track was maintained close to the northwest border for the E-3 AWACS aircraft and any Navy aircraft needing emergency fuel.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] These 24-hour air-refueling zones enabled the intense air campaign during Desert Storm.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] An additional 24/7 tanker presence was maintained over the Red Sea itself to refuel Navy F-14 Tomcats maintaining Combat Air Patrol tracks.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] During the conflict's final week, KC-10s moved inside Iraq to support barrier CAP missions set up to block Iraqi fighters from escaping to Iran.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] On 16–17 January 1991, the first combat sortie of Operation Desert Storm, and the longest combat sortie in history at that time, was launched from Barksdale AFB, Louisiana.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Seven B-52Gs flew a thirty-five-hour mission to the region and back to launch 35 Boeing Air Launched Cruise Missiles (ALCMs) with the surprise use of conventional warheads.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] This attack, which successfully destroyed 85–95 percent of intended targets, would have been impossible without the support of refueling tankers.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] An extremely useful tanker in Desert Storm was the USAF's KC-10A Extender.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] With a full jet fuel load, the KC-10A is capable of flying from a base on the American East Coast, flying nonstop to Europe, transferring a considerable amount of fuel to other aircraft, and returning to its home base without landing anywhere else.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] On 24 January 1991, the Iraqi Air Force launched the Attack on Ras Tanura, an attempt to bomb the Ras Tanura oil facility in Saudi Arabia.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] On their way to the target, the Iraqi attack aircraft were refueled by tanker at an altitude of 100 meters.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The attack ultimately failed, with two aircraft turning back and the remaining two shot down.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The Ilyushin Il-78 MKI aircraft of the Indian Air Force was deployed during the 2019 Balakot airstrike.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] The Il-78MKIs supported the Dassault Mirage 2000 and their Sukhoi Su-30MKI which acted as escort fighters.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] 152 aircraft were slated to participate in the operation, with 82 tanker aircraft providing refueling support to 70 other participating aircraft.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p01] Helicopter in-flight refueling (HIFR) is a variation of aerial refueling when a naval helicopter approaches a warship (not necessarily suited for landing operations) and receives fuel through the cabin while hovering.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p02] A mission modified Cessna 172 Skyhawk with a crew of two set the world record for the longest continuous crewed flight without landing of 64 days, 22 hours, 19 minutes, and five seconds in 1958.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p02] A Ford truck was outfitted with a fuel pump, tank, and other paraphernalia required to support the aircraft in flight.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aerial-refueling-p02] The publicity flight for a Las Vegas area hotel ended when the aircraft's performance had degraded to the point where the Cessna had difficulty climbing away from the refueling vehicle.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] An **afterburner** (or **reheat** in British English) is an additional combustion component used on some jet engines, mostly those on military supersonic aircraft.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] Its purpose is to increase thrust, usually for supersonic flight, takeoff, and combat.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] The afterburning process injects additional fuel into a combustor ("burner") in the jet pipe behind (i.e., "after") the turbine, "reheating" the exhaust gas.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] Afterburning significantly increases thrust and is used as an alternative to a larger, heavier engine.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] However, it increases fuel consumption and decreases fuel efficiency, which limits its use to short periods.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] This aircraft application of "reheat" contrasts with the meaning and implementation of "reheat" applicable to gas turbines driving electrical generators and which reduces fuel consumption.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] Jet engines are referred to as operating *wet* when afterburning and *dry* when not.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] An engine producing maximum thrust wet is at *maximum power,* while an engine producing maximum thrust dry is at *military power*.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] The first jet engine with after-burner was the E variant of the Jumo 004.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] Jet-engine thrust is an application of Newton's reaction principle, in which the engine generates thrust because it increases the momentum of the air passing through it.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] Thrust depends on two things: the velocity of the exhaust gas and the mass of the gas exiting the nozzle.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] A jet engine can produce more thrust by either accelerating the gas to a higher velocity or ejecting a greater mass of gas from the engine.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] Designing a basic turbojet engine around the second principle produces the turbofan engine, which creates slower gas, but more of it.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] Turbofans are highly fuel efficient and can deliver high thrust for long periods of time, but the design tradeoff is a large size relative to the power output.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] Generating increased power with a more compact engine for short periods can be achieved using an afterburner.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] The afterburner increases thrust primarily by accelerating the exhaust gas to a higher velocity.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] The following values and parameters are for an early jet engine, the Pratt & Whitney J57, stationary on the runway, and illustrate the high values of afterburner fuel flow, gas temperature and thrust compared to those for the engine operating within the temperature limitations for its turbine.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] The highest temperature in the engine (about 3,700 °F (2,040 °C) occurs in the combustion chamber, where fuel is burned (at an approximate rate of 8,520 lb/h (3,860 kg/h)) in a relatively small proportion of the air entering the engine.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] The combustion products have to be diluted with air from the compressor to bring the gas temperature down to a specific value, known as the Turbine Entry Temperature (TET) (1,570 °F (850 °C)), which gives the turbine an acceptable life.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] Having to reduce the temperature of the combustion products by a large amount is one of the primary limitations on how much thrust can be generated (10,200 lbf (45,000 N)).
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] The gas temperature decreases as it passes through the turbine (to 1,013 °F (545 °C)).
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] The afterburner combustor reheats the gas, but to a much higher temperature (2,540 °F (1,390 °C)) than the TET (1,570 °F (850 °C)).
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] As a result of the temperature rise in the afterburner combustor, the gas is accelerated, firstly by the heat addition, known as Rayleigh flow, then by the nozzle to a higher exit velocity than that which occurs without the afterburner.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] The mass flow is also slightly increased by the addition of the afterburner fuel.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] The thrust with afterburning is 16,000 lbf (71,000 N).
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] The visible exhaust may show *shock diamonds*, which are caused by shock waves formed due to slight differences between ambient pressure and the exhaust pressure.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] This interaction causes oscillations in the exhaust jet diameter over a short distance and causes visible banding where pressure and temperature are highest.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] Thrust may be increased by burning fuel in a turbofan's cold bypass air, instead of the mixed cold and hot flows as in most afterburning turbofans.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] An early augmented turbofan, the Pratt & Whitney TF30, used separate burning zones for the bypass and core flows with three of seven concentric spray rings in the bypass flow.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] In comparison, the afterburning Rolls-Royce Spey used a twenty chute mixer before the fuel manifolds.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] Plenum chamber burning (PCB) was partially developed for the vectored thrust Bristol Siddeley BS100 engine for the Hawker Siddeley P.1154 until the program was cancelled in 1965.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] The cold bypass and hot core flows were split between two pairs of nozzles, front and rear, in the same manner as the Rolls-Royce Pegasus, and fuel was burned in the fan air before it left the front nozzles.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] It would have given greater thrust for take-off and supersonic performance in an aircraft similar to, but bigger than, the Hawker Siddeley Harrier.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] Duct heating was used by Pratt & Whitney for their JTF17 turbofan proposal for the U.S.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] Supersonic Transport Program in 1964 and a demonstrator engine was run.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] The duct heater used an annular combustor and would be used for takeoff, climb and cruise at Mach 2.7 with different amounts of augmentation depending on aircraft weight.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] A jet engine afterburner is an extended exhaust section containing extra fuel injectors.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] Since the jet engine upstream (i.e., before the turbine) will use little of the oxygen it ingests, additional fuel can be burned after the gas flow has left the turbines.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] When the afterburner is turned on, fuel is injected and igniters are fired.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] The resulting combustion process increases the afterburner exit (nozzle entry) temperature, resulting in a significant increase in engine thrust.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] The resulting increase in afterburner exit volume flow is accommodated by increasing the throat area of the exit nozzle.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] Otherwise, if pressure is not released, the gas can flow upstream and re-ignite, possibly causing a compressor stall (or fan surge in a turbofan application).
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] Solar afterburners used on the F7U Cutlass, F-94 Starfire and F-89 Scorpion, had 2-position eyelid nozzles.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] Modern designs incorporate not only variable-geometry (VG) nozzles but multiple stages of augmentation via separate spray bars.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] To a first order, the gross thrust ratio (afterburning/dry) is directly proportional to the root of the stagnation temperature ratio across the afterburner (i.e. exit/entry).
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] Due to their high fuel consumption, afterburners are only used for short-duration, high-thrust requirements.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] These include heavy-weight or short-runway take-offs, assisting catapult launches from aircraft carriers, and during air combat.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] A notable exception is the Pratt & Whitney J58 engine used in the SR-71 Blackbird which used its afterburner for prolonged periods and was refueled in-flight as part of every reconnaissance mission.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] An afterburner has a limited life to match its intermittent use.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] The J58 was an exception with a continuous rating.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] This was achieved with thermal barrier coatings on the liner and flame holders and by cooling the liner and nozzle with compressor bleed air instead of turbine exhaust gas.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] In heat engines such as jet engines, efficiency is highest when combustion occurs at the highest pressure and temperature possible, and expanded down to ambient pressure (see Carnot cycle).
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] Since the exhaust gas already has a reduced oxygen content, owing to previous combustion, and since the fuel is not burning in a highly compressed air column, the afterburner is generally inefficient in comparison to the main combustion process.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] Afterburner efficiency also declines significantly if, as is usually the case, the inlet and tailpipe pressure decreases with increasing altitude.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] This limitation applies only to turbojets.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] In a military turbofan combat engine, the bypass air is added into the exhaust, thereby increasing the core and afterburner efficiency.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] In turbojets the gain is limited to 50%, whereas in a turbofan it depends on the bypass ratio and can be as much as 70%.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] However, as a counterexample, the SR-71 had reasonable efficiency at high altitude in afterburning ("wet") mode owing to its high speed (Mach 3.2) and correspondingly high pressure due to ram intake.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] Afterburning has a significant influence upon engine cycle choice.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] Lowering the fan pressure ratio decreases specific thrust (both dry and wet afterburning), but results in a lower temperature entering the afterburner.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] Since the afterburning exit temperature is effectively fixed, the temperature rise across the unit increases, raising the afterburner fuel flow.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] The total fuel flow tends to increase faster than the net thrust, resulting in a higher specific fuel consumption (SFC).
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] However, the corresponding dry power SFC improves (i.e. lower specific thrust).
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] The high temperature ratio across the afterburner results in a good thrust boost.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] If the aircraft burns a large percentage of its fuel with the afterburner alight, it pays to select an engine cycle with a high specific thrust (i.e. high fan pressure ratio/low bypass ratio).
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] The resulting engine is relatively fuel efficient with afterburning (i.e.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] Combat/Take-off), but thirsty in dry power.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] If, however, the afterburner is to be hardly used, a low specific thrust (low fan pressure ratio/high bypass ratio) cycle will be favored.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] Such an engine has a good dry SFC, but a poor afterburning SFC at Combat/Take-off.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] Often the engine designer is faced with a compromise between these two extremes.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] The Caproni Campini C.C.2 motorjet, designed by the Italian engineer Secondo Campini, was the first aircraft to incorporate an afterburner.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] The first flight of a C.C.2, with its afterburners operating, took place on 11 April 1941.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] Early British afterburner ("reheat") work included flight tests on a Rolls-Royce W2/B23 in a Gloster Meteor I in late 1944 and ground tests on a Power Jets W2/700 engine in mid-1945.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] This engine was destined for the Miles M.52 supersonic aircraft project.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] Early American research on the concept was done by NACA, in Cleveland, Ohio, leading to the publication of the paper "Theoretical Investigation of Thrust Augmentation of Turbojet Engines by Tail-pipe Burning" in January 1947.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] American work on afterburners in 1948 resulted in installations on early straight-wing jets such as the Pirate, Starfire and Scorpion.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] The new Pratt & Whitney J48 turbojet, at 8,000 lbf (36 kN) thrust with afterburners, would power the Grumman swept-wing fighter F9F-6, which was about to go into production.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] Other new Navy fighters with afterburners included the Chance Vought F7U-3 Cutlass, powered by two 6,000 lbf (27 kN) thrust Westinghouse J46 engines.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] In the 1950s, several large afterburning engines were developed, such as the Orenda Iroquois and the British de Havilland Gyron and Rolls-Royce Avon RB.146 variants.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] The Avon and its variants powered the English Electric Lightning, the first supersonic aircraft in RAF service.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] The Bristol-Siddeley/Rolls-Royce Olympus was fitted with afterburners for use with the BAC TSR-2.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] This system was designed and developed jointly by Bristol-Siddeley and Solar of San Diego.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] The afterburner system for the Concorde was developed by Snecma.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] Afterburners are generally used only in military aircraft, and are considered standard equipment on fighter aircraft.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] The handful of civilian planes that have used them include some NASA research aircraft, the Tupolev Tu-144, Concorde and the White Knight of Scaled Composites.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] Concorde flew long distances at supersonic speeds.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] Sustained high speeds would be impossible with the high fuel consumption of afterburner, and the plane used afterburners at takeoff and to minimize time spent in the high-drag transonic flight regime.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] Supersonic flight without afterburners is referred to as supercruise.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] A turbojet engine equipped with an afterburner is called an "afterburning turbojet", whereas a turbofan engine similarly equipped is sometimes called an "augmented turbofan".
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] A "dump-and-burn" is an airshow display feature where fuel is jettisoned, then intentionally ignited using the afterburner.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] A spectacular flame combined with high speed makes this a popular display for airshows, or as a finale to fireworks.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] Fuel dumping is used primarily to reduce the weight of an aircraft to avoid a heavy, high-speed landing.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/afterburner] Other than for safety or emergency reasons, fuel dumping does not have a practical use.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] Air-cooled engines are widely seen in applications where weight or simplicity is the primary goal.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] Their simplicity makes them suited for uses in small applications like chainsaws and lawn mowers, as well as small generators and similar roles.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] These qualities also make them highly suitable for aviation use, where they are widely used in general aviation aircraft and as auxiliary power units on larger aircraft.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] Their simplicity, in particular, also makes them common on motorcycles.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] Most modern internal combustion engines are cooled by a closed circuit carrying liquid coolant through channels in the engine block and cylinder head.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] A fluid in these channels absorbs heat and then flows to a heat exchanger or radiator where the coolant releases heat into the air (or raw water, in the case of marine engines).
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] Thus, while they are not *ultimately* cooled by the liquid, as the heat is exchanged with some other fluid like air, because of the liquid-coolant circuit they are known as *liquid-cooled*.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] In contrast, heat generated by an air-cooled engine is released directly into the air.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] Typically this is facilitated with metal fins covering the outside of the cylinder head and cylinders which increase the surface area that air can act on.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] Air may be force fed with the use of a fan and shroud to achieve efficient cooling with high volumes of air or simply by natural air flow with well designed and angled fins.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] In all combustion engines, a great percentage of the heat generated, around 44%, escapes through the exhaust.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] Another 8% or so ends up in the oil, which itself has to be cooled in an oil cooler.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] This means less than half of the heat has to be removed through other systems.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] In an air-cooled engine, only about 12% of the heat flows out through the metal fins.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] Air cooled engines usually run noisier, however it provides more simplicity which gives benefits when it comes to servicing and part replacement and is usually cheaper to be maintained.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] Many motorcycles use air cooling for the sake of reducing weight and complexity.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] Few current production automobiles have air-cooled engines (such as Tatra 815), but historically it was common for many high-volume vehicles.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] The orientation of the engine cylinders is commonly found in either single-cylinder or coupled in groups of two, and cylinders are commonly oriented in a horizontal fashion as a flat engine, while vertical straight-four engine have been used.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] During the 1920s and 30s there was a great debate in the aviation industry about the merits of air-cooled vs. liquid-cooled designs.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] At the beginning of this period, the liquid used for cooling was water at ambient pressure.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] The amount of heat carried away by a fluid is a function of its capacity and the difference in input and output temperatures.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] As the boiling point of water is reduced with lower pressure, and the water could not be efficiently pumped as steam, radiators had to have enough cooling power to account for the loss in cooling power as the aircraft climbed.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] The resulting radiators were quite large and caused a significant amount of aerodynamic drag.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] This placed the two designs roughly equal in terms of power to drag, but the air-cooled designs were almost always lighter and simpler.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] In 1921, the US Navy, largely due to the efforts of Commander Bruce G.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] Leighton, decided that the simplicity of the air-cooled design would result in less maintenance workload, which was paramount given the limited working area of aircraft carriers.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] Leighton's efforts led to the Navy underwriting air-cooled engine development at Pratt & Whitney and Wright Aeronautical.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] Most other groups, especially in Europe where aircraft performance was rapidly improving, were more concerned with the issue of drag.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] While air-cooled designs were common on light aircraft and trainers, as well as some transport aircraft and bombers, liquid-cooled designs remained much more common for fighters and high-performance bombers.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] The drag issue was upset by the 1929 introduction of the NACA cowl, which greatly reduced the drag of air-cooled engines in spite of their larger frontal area, and the drag related to cooling was at this point largely even.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] This also led to development work attempting to eliminate the radiator entirely using evaporative cooling, allowing it to turn to steam and running the steam through tubes located just under the skin of the wings and fuselage, where the fast moving outside air condensed it back to water.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] While this concept was used on a number of record-setting aircraft in the late 1930s, it always proved impractical for production aircraft for a wide variety of reasons.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] In 1929, Curtiss began experiments replacing water with ethylene glycol in a Curtiss D-12 engine.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] Ethylene glycol could run up to 250°C and reduced the radiator size by 50% compared to water-cooled designs.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] The experiments were extremely successful and by 1932 the company had switched all future designs to this coolant.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] At the time, Union Carbide held a monopoly on the industrial process to make ethylene glycol, so it was initially used only in the US, with Allison Engines picking it up soon after.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] It was not until the mid-1930s that Rolls-Royce adopted it as supplies improved, converting all of their engines to ethylene glycol.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] With the much smaller radiators and less fluid in the system, the weight and drag of these designs was well below contemporary air-cooled designs.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] On a weight basis, these liquid-cooled designs offered as much as 30% better performance.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] In the late- and post-war era, the high-performance field quickly moved to jet engines.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] This took away the primary market for late-model liquid-cooled engines.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] Those roles that remained with piston power were mostly slower designs and civilian aircraft.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] In these roles, the simplicity and reduction in servicing needs is far more important than drag, and from the end of the war on almost all piston aviation engines have been air-cooled, with few exceptions.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] As of 2020, most of the engines manufactured by Lycoming and Continental are used by major manufacturers of light aircraft Cirrus, Cessna and so on.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] Other engine manufactures using air-cooled engine technology are ULPower and Jabiru, more active in the Light-Sport Aircraft (LSA) and ultralight aircraft market.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] Rotax uses a combination of air-cooled cylinders and liquid-cooled cylinder heads.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] Some small diesel engines, e.g. those made by Deutz AG and Lister Petter are air-cooled.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] Probably the only big Euro 5 truck air-cooled engine (V8 320 kW power 2100 N·m torque one) is being produced by Tatra.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] BOMAG part of the FAYAT group also utilizes an air cooled inline 6 cylinder motor, in many of their construction vehicles.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] Stationary or portable engines were commercially introduced early in the 1900s.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] The first commercial production was by the New Way Motor Company of Lansing, Michigan, US.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] The company produced air-cooled engines in single and twin cylinders in both horizontal and vertical cylinder format.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] Subsequent to their initial production which was exported worldwide, other companies took up the advantages of this cooling method, especially in small portable engines.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-cooled-engine] Applications include mowers, generators, outboard motors, pump sets, saw benches and auxiliary power plants and more.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-start-system] An **air-start system** is a power source used to provide the initial rotation to start large diesel engines and gas turbines.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-start-system] Compared to a gasoline (petrol) engine, a diesel engine has a very high compression ratio, an essential design feature, as it is the heat of compression that ignites the fuel.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-start-system] An electric starter with sufficient power to turn a large diesel engine would itself be so large as to be impractical so there is a need for an alternative system.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-start-system] An air start system has three main components along with various safety components, namely the air start injector, the distributor and the air receivers.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-start-system] When the system is initiated, starting air from the receivers is distributed by the distributor unit to each respective air start valve according to the firing order of the engine’s cylinders.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-start-system] Safety components include flame traps, to prevent air line explosions, a turning gear interlock which ensures that air-start cannot be initiated when the turning gear is engaged, relief valves and isolation valves, as well as drain valves at certain points along the system.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-start-system] Control components include the control valves and remote air-start valves.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-start-system] A direct start system as used on a marine slow-speed diesel is required to have up to 12 starts on a non-reversing engine or 6 starts on a reversible, or geared, engine.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-start-system] When starting the engine, compressed air is admitted to whichever cylinder has a piston just over top dead center, forcing it downward.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-start-system] As the engine starts to turn, the air-start valve on the next cylinder in line opens to continue the rotation.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-start-system] After several rotations, fuel is injected into the cylinders, the engine starts running and the air is cut off.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-start-system] To further complicate matters, a large engine is usually "blown over" first with zero fuel settings and the indicator cocks open, to prove that the engine is clear of any water build up and that everything is free to turn.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-start-system] After a successful blow ahead and a blow astern, the indicator cocks are closed on all the cylinders, and then the engine can be started on fuel.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-start-system] Significant complexity is added to the engine by using an air-start system, as the cylinder head must have an extra valve in each cylinder to admit the air in for starting, plus the required control systems.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-start-system] This added complexity and cost limits the use of air-starters to very large and expensive reciprocating engines.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-start-system] Another method of air-starting an internal combustion engine is by using compressed air or gas to drive a fluid motor in place of an electric motor.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-start-system] They can be used to start engines from 5 to 320 liters in size and if more starting power is necessary two or more motors can be used.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-start-system] Starters of this type are used in place of electric motors because of their lighter weight and higher reliability.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-start-system] They can also outlast an electric starter by a factor of three and are easier to rebuild.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-start-system] Engines operating in underground mining activities tend to operate on this type of starter system to reduce the risk of an electrical system igniting flammable material.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-start-system] All vane type air starters should have a lubricator installed to insure long-life and maximum performance.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-start-system] Lubricators give the moving parts a needed friction barrier, reduce metal corrosion and keep vanes sealed properly against the cylinder walls.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-start-system] Even the so-called lube-free air starters require lubrication to prolong trouble free life.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-start-system] Two basic lubricator devices are typically employed.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-start-system] One is an in-line or reservoir type that typically stores up to 2 quarts of lubricant, and is installed along the air supply line.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-start-system] The second style of lubricator is a small one shot device that dispenses a measured amount of lubricant every time the starter is engaged.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-start-system] Installed directly onto the air inlet of the starter, the in-line lubricators are self priming pneumatic pumps that require a 1/4″ lubrication line piped from as far away as 4 feet.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-start-system] Air Starter lubricators perform best using misting type, non-detergent oils such as diesel fuel or Marvel Mystery oil.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-start-system] If emissions are a concern, there are environmentally friendly type lubricants available on the market.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-start-system] Not all air starters require lubrication.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-start-system] Turbine type air starters do not require air motor lubrication, although some turbine air starters do use an oil filled transmission that may require periodic inspections and maintenance.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-start-system] Compressed air has been used to start gas turbine engines using air impingement starting (in which air is directed at the engine turbine blades through nozzles in the turbine casing, used on US Navy General Electric J79 engines).
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-start-system] It is much more efficient to use an air turbine starter (ATS) which is usually mounted on an accessory gearbox.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-start-system] An early axial compressor turbojet had an ATS located in the compressor nose cone (eg particular variants of the J79).
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-start-system] Air impingement starting was not used for US military aircraft after the F-4B, A-5A and F-5 as the pneumatic energy requirement was several times greater than when using an air turbine starter.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-start-system] The gas turbine compressor required to start a J79 with impingement starting was sufficient to start two J79 engines simultaneously in a B-58 when using air turbine starters.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-start-system] An ATS has its own turbine and gears to change its low torque and high speed to low speed and high torque at the engine mounting pad.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-start-system] Further gears in the engine gearbox connect to the engine shaft (high pressure spool on multi-spool engines).
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-start-system] Compared with electric starters, air-starters have a higher power-to-weight ratio so are used on large engines as an electric starter would be too big and, with its cables, too heavy and expensive.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-start-system] However, for smaller engines, which don't need as much starter power, an electric starter is more suitable.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-start-system] It has a dual function as a generator (is known as a starter/generator) at speeds above which the engine no longer requires starter assistance.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-turborocket] The **air turborocket** is a form of combined-cycle jet engine.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-turborocket] The basic layout includes a gas generator, which produces high pressure gas, that drives a turbine/compressor assembly which compresses atmospheric air into a combustion chamber.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-turborocket] This mixture is then combusted before leaving the device through a nozzle and creating thrust.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-turborocket] There are many different types of air turborockets.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-turborocket] The various types generally differ in how the gas generator section of the engine functions.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-turborocket] Air turborockets are often referred to as **turboramjets**, **turboramjet rockets**, **turborocket expanders**, and many others.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-turborocket] As there is no consensus on which names apply to which specific concepts, various sources may use the same name for two different concepts.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-turborocket] The benefit of this setup is increased specific impulse over that of a rocket.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-turborocket] For the same carried mass of propellant as a rocket motor, the overall output of the air turborocket is much higher.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-turborocket] In addition, it provides thrust throughout a much wider speed range than a ramjet, yet is much cheaper and easier to control than a gas turbine engine.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-turborocket] The air turborocket fills a niche (in terms of cost, reliability, ruggedness, and duration of thrust) between the solid-fuel rocket motor and gas turbine engine for missile applications.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-turborocket] A **turborocket** is a type of aircraft engine combining elements of a jet engine and a rocket.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-turborocket] It typically comprises a multi-stage fan driven by a turbine, which is driven by the hot gases exhausting from a series of small rocket-like motors mounted around the turbine inlet.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-turborocket] The turbine exhaust gases mix with the fan discharge air, and combust with the air from the compressor before exhausting through a convergent-divergent propelling nozzle.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-turborocket] Once a jet engine goes high enough in an atmosphere, there is insufficient oxygen to burn the jet fuel.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-turborocket] The idea behind a turborocket is to supplement the atmospheric oxygen with an onboard supply.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-turborocket] This allows operation at a much higher altitude than a normal engine would allow.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-turborocket] The turborocket design offers a mixture of benefits with drawbacks.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-turborocket] It is not a true rocket, so it cannot operate in space.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-turborocket] Cooling the engine is not a problem because the burner and its hot exhaust gases are located behind the turbine blades.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-turborocket] The air turboramjet engine is a combined cycle engine that merges aspects of turbojet and ramjet engines.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-turborocket] The turboramjet is a hybrid engine that essentially consists of a turbojet mounted inside a ramjet.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-turborocket] The turbojet core is mounted inside a duct that contains a combustion chamber downstream of the turbojet nozzle.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-turborocket] The turboramjet can be run in turbojet mode at takeoff and during low-speed flight but then switch to ramjet mode to accelerate to high Mach numbers.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-turborocket] The operation of the engine is controlled using bypass flaps located just downstream of the diffuser.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-turborocket] During low-speed flight, controllable flaps close the bypass duct and force air directly into the compressor section of the turbojet.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-turborocket] During high-speed flight, the flaps block the flow into the turbojet, and the engine operates like a ramjet using the *aft* combustion chamber to produce thrust.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-turborocket] The engine would start out operating as a turbojet during takeoff and while climbing to altitude.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-turborocket] Upon reaching high subsonic speed, the portion of the engine downstream of the turbojet would be used as an afterburner to accelerate the plane above the speed of sound.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-turborocket] At lower speeds, air passes through an inlet and is then compressed by an axial compressor.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-turborocket] That compressor is driven by a turbine, which is powered by hot, high-pressure gas from a combustion chamber.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-turborocket] These initial aspects are very similar to how a turbojet operates, however, there are several differences.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-turborocket] The first is that the combustor in the turboramjet is often separate from the main airflow.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-turborocket] Instead of combining air from the compressor with fuel to combust, the turboramjet combustor may use hydrogen and oxygen, carried on the aircraft, as its fuel for the combustor.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-turborocket] The air compressed by the compressor bypasses the combustor and turbine section of the engine, where it is mixed with the turbine exhaust.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-turborocket] The turbine exhaust can be designed to be fuel-rich (i.e., the combustor does not burn all the fuel) which, when mixed with the compressed air, creates a hot fuel-air mixture which is ready to burn again.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-turborocket] More fuel is injected into this air where it is again combusted.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-turborocket] The exhaust is ejected through a propelling nozzle, generating thrust.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-turborocket] Picture shown lacks required bypass ducting around the compressor for ramjet operation.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-turborocket] Shown is a low bypass turbojet with re-heat.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-turborocket] The turboramjet engine is used when space is constrained, as it takes up less space than separate ramjet and turbojet engines.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-turborocket] Since a ramjet must already be traveling at high speeds before it will start working, a ramjet-powered aircraft is incapable of taking off from a runway under its own power; that is the advantage of the turbojet, which is a member of the gas turbine family of engines.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-turborocket] A turbojet does not rely purely on the motion of the engine to compress the incoming air flow; instead, the turbojet contains some additional rotating machinery that compresses incoming air and allows the engine to function during takeoff and at slow speeds.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-turborocket] In applications which stay relatively in the atmosphere and require longer durations of lower thrust over a specific speed range the air turborocket can have a weight advantage over the standard solid fuel rocket motor.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/air-turborocket] In terms of volumetric requirements, the rocket motor has the advantage due to the lack of inlet ducts and other air management devices.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aircraft-fuel-system] An **aircraft fuel system** allows the crew to pump, manage, and deliver aviation fuel to the propulsion system and auxiliary power unit (APU) of an aircraft.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aircraft-fuel-system] Fuel systems differ greatly due to different performance of the aircraft in which they are installed.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aircraft-fuel-system] A single-engine piston aircraft has a simple fuel system, while a tanker (such as the KC-135) not only manages its own fuel but can also provide fuel to other aircraft.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aircraft-fuel-system] Fuel is piped through fuel lines to a fuel control valve (usually known as the fuel selector).
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aircraft-fuel-system] The first function is to act as a fuel shut-off valve.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aircraft-fuel-system] This is required to provide the crew with a means to prevent fuel reaching the engine in case of an engine fire.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aircraft-fuel-system] The second function is to allow the pilot to choose which tank feeds the engine.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aircraft-fuel-system] Many aircraft have the left tank and right tank selections available to the pilot.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aircraft-fuel-system] Some Cessna airplanes feed only from both tanks; and many have the option to feed from left, right, or both tanks.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aircraft-fuel-system] The reason to have left only and right only options is to allow pilots to balance fuel load to reduce the banking moment.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aircraft-fuel-system] In some aircraft, the shut-off function is a different valve located after the fuel selector valve.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aircraft-fuel-system] Typically, after the selector valve—situated at a low point in the fuel run—there is a gascolator — a fuel filter that can be opened on the ground and drained of fuel impurities denser than petroleum, mainly water and sediment.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aircraft-fuel-system] Other drainage points are in each tank (often more than one contaminant collection sump per tank) and at the injection pump.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aircraft-fuel-system] Each tank is vented (or pressurised) to allow air into the tank to take the place of burned fuel; otherwise, the tank would be in negative pressure which would result in engine fuel starvation.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aircraft-fuel-system] A vent also allows for changes in atmospheric pressure and temperature.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aircraft-fuel-system] The fuel level indication system in the simplest form is a transparent window on the tank side and in its usual application a float-driven potentiometer installed in the tank.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aircraft-fuel-system] After the TWA Flight 800 disaster, a revision was made to aircraft fuel systems to address the potential explosion hazard of electrical components located in the fuel tank.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aircraft-fuel-system] Single-engine piston aircraft fuel level systems moved to utilize float level gauges from the CNG and LPG industries which had the float drive a magnetic coupling and relocated the potentiometer outside the fuel tank.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aircraft-fuel-system] Some single-engine aircraft use capacitive probes in the fuel tanks.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aircraft-fuel-system] As fuel is burned, more air enters the tank and the capacitance decreases; this is read by a computer and the fuel amount is calculated and displayed to the pilots.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aircraft-fuel-system] Recent advances in magnetoresistive technology have evolved new fuel level sensors for general aviation applications.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aircraft-fuel-system] This system is not affected by any additive or fuel combination to replace 100LL for piston-powered aircraft.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aircraft-fuel-system] Single-engine light aircraft fuel tanks are usually in the wings, but some aircraft have a small "header tank" between the normal fuel tank and the engine, to facilitate reliable fuel flow to the engine.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aircraft-fuel-system] On many small or very old single-engine aircraft, header tanks (and even main tanks) are often mounted above and/or immediately behind the engine.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aircraft-fuel-system] A few (particularly ultralight aircraft) have them in the fuselage or on the airframe behind the pilot and/or passenger(s).
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aircraft-fuel-system] Adding tanks and engines increases the complexity of the fuel system and its management.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aircraft-fuel-system] All of the considerations made for the twin piston are applicable to turbine fuel systems.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aircraft-fuel-system] Additional consideration apply because of the higher altitudes, different fuel, lower temperatures, and longer flights.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aircraft-fuel-system] To avoid water condensation or the fuel itself solidifying at low temperatures (−55 °C), fuel tanks have thermometers and heating systems.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aircraft-fuel-system] Many are pressurized with engine bleed air to keep moist air out and ensure positive pressure feed to the pumps.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aircraft-fuel-system] In larger aircraft, fuel tanks also are in the fuselage and their load affects the center of gravity of the aircraft.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aircraft-fuel-system] This imposes limitations on the amount of fuel carried and the order in which fuel must be used.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aircraft-fuel-system] Turbine engines burn fuel faster than reciprocating engines do.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aircraft-fuel-system] Because fuel needs to be injected in to a combustor, the injection system of a turbine aircraft must provide fuel at higher pressure and flow compared to that for a piston engine aircraft.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aircraft-fuel-system] The refueling system of larger aircraft includes a single positive pressure refueling point from which all tanks can be fueled.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aircraft-fuel-system] How much and to which tanks fuel is fed during refueling operations is determined by the controls in the refueling panel, usually installed nearby and accessible to ground crews.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aircraft-fuel-system] External tanks are used to extend the range of an aircraft.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aircraft-fuel-system] Drop tanks are used by combat aircraft that need to discard them after use for performance reasons.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aircraft-fuel-system] A fuel pump is required to transfer fuel from a tip tank to a main tank.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aopa-pilot] The **Aircraft Owners and Pilots Association** (**AOPA**) is a Frederick, Maryland-based American non-profit political organization that advocates for general aviation.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aopa-pilot] AOPA's membership consists mainly of general aviation pilots in the United States.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aopa-pilot] AOPA exists to serve the interests of its members as aircraft owners and pilots and to promote the economy, safety, utility, and popularity of flight in general aviation aircraft.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aopa-pilot] With 384,915 members in 2012, AOPA is the largest aviation association in the world, although it had decreased in membership from 414,224 in 2010, a loss of 7% in two years.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aopa-pilot] AOPA is affiliated with other similar organizations in other countries through membership in the International Council of Aircraft Owner and Pilot Associations (IAOPA).
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aopa-pilot] In 2015, AOPA was inducted into the International Air & Space Hall of Fame at the San Diego Air & Space Museum.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aopa-pilot] In September 2024, the AOPA appointed Darren Pleasance as its sixth President and CEO.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aopa-pilot] Pleasance, with extensive experience in aviation and business, is set to officially assume the role on January 1, 2025.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aopa-pilot] However, just over a year after taking on the role, Pleasance was removed by the board for unclear reasons.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aopa-pilot] The organization started at Wings Field in Blue Bell, Pennsylvania.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aopa-pilot] On 24 April 1932, The Philadelphia Aviation Country Club was founded at Wings Field.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aopa-pilot] The country club was the location of meetings of members that founded AOPA.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aopa-pilot] AOPA incorporated on May 15, 1939, with Charles Townsend Ludington serving as the first president.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aopa-pilot] In 1971 the organization purchased *Airport World Magazine*, moving its operations to Bethesda, Maryland.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aopa-pilot] On 1 October 2023, Senior Vice President of AOPA Air Safety Institute Richard McSpadden was killed in an aircraft accident near Lake Placid, New York.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aopa-pilot] In November 2024 Mark Baker, the President and CEO of the AOPA, addressed concerns regarding the negative impact of increased customs fees on businesses in the Bahamas.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aopa-pilot] These fees, which have been imposed on private aircraft flying into the region, have drawn criticism from the AOPA since the summer of 2024.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aopa-pilot] Baker emphasized the potential risks to tourism and local economies, urging policymakers to reconsider the fees to prevent a decline in aviation-driven tourism and business activity in the Bahamas.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aopa-pilot] AOPA sponsors its own Fly-In and open house in Frederick, Maryland.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aopa-pilot] The yearly event started in 1991 with 125 aircraft.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aopa-pilot] By 2001, the attendance grew to 760 aircraft.
[src:aircraft-fuel-system/aopa-pilot] The event was cancelled for five years after the September 11, 2001 attacks and consequent airspace changes, but resumed in 2006.
